The Trojan horse of Europe
Berkeley – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will have to be provided.
Conditions will have to be attached.
The Greek government will make the usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to service its debt.
The markets will calm down.
Long-term consequences will not be disastrous, but there will be problems ahead.
Some will say that the fatal mistake was allowing Greece to adopt the euro in the first place.
It was already evident that the country was not ready.
Its budgetary policy was already uncontrolled when it joined the monetary union in 2001, and its unions were already pressuring for Greek wages to align with those practiced in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this response is too simplistic, as such signs of dysfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with a 20% unemployment rate and abyssal budget deficits, sees Greece as an image of its own future.
And if not, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy are doing somewhat better.
These countries, just like Greece, must face significant budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot devalue their currency to boost exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to seek aid.
All of this raises one question: wasn't the real mistake creating the euro?
Insofar as I was one of the few Americans who encouraged the idea of a European currency, you might rightly ask: are you reconsidering your initial position?
My answer is no, creating the euro was not a mistake, but it could well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway along the path to a viable monetary union.
If it does nothing, the next crisis could well make this one look like a walk in the park.
If it wants to complete its monetary union, Europe will have to create its own emergency financing mechanism.
Today, members of the Union can only provide aid to Greece by circumventing the regulations that prevent them from granting a loan except in the case of natural disasters or circumstances beyond a country's control.
This exacerbates the uncertainty.
When European leaders provide aid, public opinion and markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems result from the Lisbon Treaty, then it must be amended.
Moreover, aid should not be granted only under certain conditions, but should be accompanied by temporary national budget control by a committee of "experts" appointed by the European Union.
The history shows that simple promises made by recipient countries are not enough.
Of course, countries subjected to such measures will express their outrage.
But no one is forcing them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Notice that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the defunct Stability and Growth Pact.
We could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily handed over its budget to an expert specifically appointed by President Barack Obama's administration?
In fact, it would not bother them too much.
The expert would not be of Californian origin, but American.
The public would understand that he would act in the interest of the Californian state as well as the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from whom these orders would emanate, would reassure them.
Europeans do not do such things because they first and foremost see themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the «sovereignty prerogatives» of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant given its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties, but also closer political ties.
Those with a solid emergency aid mechanism will really have to account for it.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel hates this kind of bailout because they know very well who will be responsible.
The Germans oppose anything that resembles European political integration.
But Germany also has a share of responsibility in this crisis.
It wanted an incredibly independent central bank that was not obligated to account for its actions, but today it has adopted an overly excessive monetary policy, thereby critically worsening the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
Germany's huge current surpluses further exacerbate their situation.
In addition, its fiscal stimulus measures were not sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has significantly benefited from the creation of the euro.
She should do the same.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency loan facility, as well as political integration to make it possible.
She must provide more budgetary support.
Isn't she best positioned to push for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that leads Europe toward more advanced political integration.
We can only hope.
